In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, as some medicines are already available.
AIDS can’t be cured until now.
However, the lives of patients can be significantly prolonged thanks to a mixture of drugs that prevent the replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the replication of the virus is not completely suppressed, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, the drugs no longer work.
The work of experts from three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, V<0xC5><0xA0>CHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg demonstrates the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They demonstrated that substances called metalocarbons have an effect on albumin, which is responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
The metallocarbons are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way than all the drugs used today, and therefore can solve the resistance problem.
In their work, scientists find new, ‘improved’ compounds, prepared knowing the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus’s albumin.
Metalocarbons have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyedric cages composed of the boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are joined by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus
HIV proteasis is an albumin of the HIV virus, and is essential for the virus's vital cycle.
Without HIV proteasis, the HIV virus is not fracturing and no mature and infectious corpuscles of the virus would be created.
If we stop HIV proteasis, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient’s body, the scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In an article published in the Journal of Medical Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds, in which two pairs of cages (see table) are joined by a short organic series, which continues to be systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more effective
The test of the effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was performed in probe, and also against its resistant variants, obtained from HIV patients.
The effect of metallocarbons on the common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as in clinically used drugs, however they do not lose their effect on resistant variants, in which drugs often do not work.
The mechanism of the unique effect, its other qualities such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical modifications makes metallocarbons interesting compounds for research with the aim of proposing effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlína <0xC5><0xA0>ezá<0xC4><0x8D>ová, the head of the biodemiology laboratory at the Institute of Organic Biology and the Institute of Chemical Structural Biology.
