The Management Revolution or the End of Business Intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain.
More than a decade ago, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees recalls the position of the companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about employees adhering to "values" determined from above as before it was about imposing on consumers products thought by farica technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave rise to strategies to conquer the markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are not related to customer preference factors is repeated regularly.
Demobilization of employees can result in a deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R&D and, more importantly, business intelligence.
Indeed, the BI (Business Intelligence) "requires that all parties involved (...) have a proactive conduct and a forward-looking vision"; it needs on the part of employees a commitment that completely opposes the recommendations of an authoritarian direction.
For this reason, we call for a management revolution, which would consist of putting the employees at the center of the company’s concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have a relative utility
Will internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire carried out by Orange among its employees, incentivize the managerial revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many turns, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!
Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
Finally, because most executives have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great schools of engineers, they interpret psychology in a mechanical way.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the ancient behavioral theory that American "neurosciences" recently reactivated, and that Institutes of Studies and the media spread widely on their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "commands" (sic) of the executives' commitment, a recent research by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms the executives in a posture of mechanistic management, inadapted to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the management revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises involves adopting a finalist view of human behavior.
It consists in integrating into every reasoning or practice of business management, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to make reality part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from Motivational Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
Studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of mobilization factors, business managers can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and relocate human resources management "on the spot".
In this way, they create a favorable ground for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
