The cradle of the dinosaur
The Tawa hallae looked the same as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: a two-metre-long and 1.50-metre-high animal running over the two strong rear legs, had an elongated head with sharp and curved teeth, short arms with claws in the form of a cloud and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, it would not have been anything special.
But the Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at that time was in a dry area of the supercontinent Pangea in Ecuador.
Tawa opened a new window to the early evolution of dinosaurs, Nesbitt comments.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, the spread and characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists started an excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes, we have found in one day a dozen dinosaur bones, this is something unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis, a member of the Utah Museum of Natural History team.
The researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation, the remains of five specimens were collected in total.
A finding confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional finding: "Triace dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not share such enthusiasm at all.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, for example, comments Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current opinion stream, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these first dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts debate, for example, when saurys were divided into their three most important genealogical lines: carnivorous theropods among which are the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also birds, the sauropods aveene, the quadrupeds Orbíris, the "length neck" and the pelvises, and their relatives.
According to analysis by Nesbitt and colleagues, Tawa hallae is a primitive theropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, comments Nesbitt.
For example, in Tawa's skull, the researchers found clues of airbags, such as those also possessed by the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to airbags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa, the bones of the spine were also evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive airbag theropod, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of the later giant sauropods also possessed air bags and light bones, it was likely that the common predecessors of both groups already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migratory waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, researchers deduce that the saury originated there for the first time.
Therefore, the three genealogical lines were separated at first and spread from South America across all corners of the Earth, which by then still formed a unique earth mass, the supercontinent Pangea.
However, the facts say that the team found along with Tawa find the remains of two other theropods not very closely related.
The three cannot descend from a single related ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there have been at least three migration waves to North America, comments Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the study Science.
Of course, there are opponents as well.
An even older species, Silesaurus, belonging to a brother group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, comments Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could give a distorted image, because in South America simply many fossils of dinosaurs are still preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs evolved from a relatively rare collar line from reptiles to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of the Mesozoic remains an enigma.
In the Triassic, dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of current crocodiles and pterosaurs and many other saurians.
By the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs expanded around the world and many new species developed, while the kinship extinguished on the Triassic boundary towards the Jurassic.
Successful stories weren't eternal
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, comments Martin Sander.
There may have been a massive extinction that the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they could defeat the opponents in the area.
Successful stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact slowed the rise of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triassic and since then had a miserable existence: mammals.
