In psychosis I have experienced the most terrible distress and the deepest despair, he says.
Hallucinations are a cruel reality
Approximately one percent of the population falls ill at least once in their life of schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, most often those affected can no longer distinguish between the outside world and the inside, and fall into a state of overexcitation that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of greatness, disorders in the relationship, or persecutory mania.
Especially extended is the hearing of voices: voices that give orders, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The affected person is no longer able to distinguish what is important from what is not, the brain can no longer filter the disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like sleep, psychosis opens the door to a stream of ideas and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is focused on the subject, says professor Thomas Fuchs, doctor-in-chief of the general psychiatric clinic at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of events, everything has a meaning directed to it.
At the same time, he enters a passive role, as in a dream, he feels overwhelmed by events and cannot actively organize them.
This is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
In general, it is not possible to adjust reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, waking up, impossible.
Having experienced a hallucination once in life
Unlike in a dream, Fuchs says, “the spatial and sensory structure of reality that is perceived in psychosis remains in principle as it is.”
Paranoid thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the distance from the experience takes place in reality.
For researchers still an unknown reason why our brains make cabrioles.
According to Fuchs, state of emergency can lead anyone to lose contact with reality temporarily.
But not everyone develops a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic disposition for schizophrenia, but studies in twins have shown that in addition to the genes, there are also other determinants.
Researchers suggest that those affected suffer minimal brain damage.
We suspect that the neuronal maturity of the brain is affected at an early stage of development, such as through a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But it remains an unknown how this alteration of the nervous system occurs, which also does not manifest itself at all for many years.
The influence of the environment also plays an important role – stress or a traumatic experience can be the triggers of a psychosis when a pre-arrangement already exists.
Similarly, hallucinogen drugs can cause psychosis, as they interfere with the transmitting system of the brain.
When the brain warms up
The illogical thing about all this is that psychotic people suffer from their hallucinations and take very expensive medications to get rid of them, while others pay for drugs that allow them to experiment with some, says psychology professor Erich Kasten of Lübeck.
Perceiving a hallucination as pleasant or not often depends on the point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports of hallucinations and visions for ten years and has analyzed the results in the book Die unreale Welt in unserem Kopf, published last year.
Hallucinations are among the typical accompanying symptoms of psychosis, but also, surprisingly, many other diseases.
Among them, along with mental disorders such as personality limit disorder or depression, often also diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's and cranioencephalic trauma.
Surprisingly and under certain conditions, the brain of healthy people also suffers from hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are composed of memories that are usually suppressed.
They arise when the areas of the brain in which sensory perceptions are processed are hyperactive or are little coercive; when our brain warms up, but also when stimuli are missing.
Drugs can cause this condition in the same way as brain damage or psychosis.
But also the restriction of stimuli, stress, bad love or other exceptional brain states.
In recent studies, up to a third of respondents reported having experienced hallucinations at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. was 16 years old, living in a small town in Mecklenburg-West Pomerania and attending a secondary school.
A hot girl.
If it wasn't for those pictures and voices.
Sometimes, during recreation, it happens that a boy with long, dark hair turns the word to him.
When she answers, the other students stare at her; no one, apart from her, hears or sees the boy.
They think the timid girl is a slightly strange dreamer, but Sarah K. knows she’s not dreaming.
She is awake and she sees and hears that boy, just as she sees and hears the girl sitting on the bench next door.
You can even feel your presence, at least for a few moments.
It's a nice feeling, he likes the guy.
Sometimes she asks if she’s crazy.
He also knows that the boy and the rest of the visions are not real and disappear.
At night, the appearances are alarming.
Visions are often a burden.
When you’re in class sometimes you can’t follow the lesson because the teacher – in his eyes and ears – is presenting a new colleague, while for the rest explains mathematical equations in a visible and audible way.
At night, the appearances are alarming.
While waiting in the dark room for the sleep to arrive, which often comes late and is scarce, she does not know whether she is awake or dreaming, whether the images she sees, the skulls or the girl with bleeding cuts in her arms and legs, appear in front of her eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, yelling at the figures.
He hasn't told his parents and friends anything, they'd think he's crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. Today is 20 years old.
She passed selectivity last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago the hallucinations disappeared.
Since she's been in contact over the Internet with psychologist Kasten, she knows she's not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art for despair.
According to Kasten, when a person is socially isolated or suffers from a restriction of stimuli, it is very likely that after a while they begin to have hallucinations.
I think the brain is unoccupied and takes care of it for entertainment.
Sarah K., a single daughter, was little afraid of the other children and often played alone.
His hallucinations began when, at the age of 13, he learned that the man he called Dad since he had used reason is not his biological father.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations are active in the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and noise, those affected like Sarah K. It is difficult to distinguish between vision and reality. “Every experience,” says Kasten, “is taking place in the brain, reality is projected there.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain produces, which is why they seem so real.”
Kasten also classifies night fantasies as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their visions as unreal.
Kasten therefore recommends his patients to appreciate his hallucinations as a special skill.
The boundary between sleep and hallucination
In this world too consciously focused, imaginary experiences usually become pathological, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, a professor in Heidelberg and head of the psychiatric and psychotherapy clinic at the Florence-Nightingale-Krankenhäusers hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a hard and painful disease but it also involves something positive and creative – madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has investigated the so-called oneirism, a special form of consciousness, which is perceived as a dream.
Oniric hallucinations are almost very complex and detailed dreams that the person who experiences them considers real and that subsequently cannot differentiate from being awake.
Oniric conscious states arise in extreme situations associated with trauma or disease, such as in patients with polyradiculoneuropathy, who experience motor paralysis being fully aware.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened by a loss of himself or the world due to a total and permanent motor incapacity, it replaces a very dangerous real situation with a self-imaginary world that is uncoupled from reality.
A form of boundary situation between sleep and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, a world change occurs, although the real situation remains present in the imagination.
An intensive way of giving meaning and interpretation to an unparalleled situation in itself that our own ability to create allows us not to sink into nothing of the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
Art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen of Zurich also describes his oniric experiences in his book Herzwechsel as an action to save the soul.
He was 49 years old, when his conscience embarked on several-day trips after a heart valve surgery with a heart transplant included, while his body was sentenced to immobility at the intensive care station.
Claussen plunged into a world created by him and visited strange places of other times: he saw himself lying in bed, an older man on board a sanatorium in a train, a robot guarded for his health.
It was seen in the High Middle Ages, surrounded by nobles who produced narcotics from blood.
A Greek on a motorbike kidnapped him in his home country, surfed his hospital bed in the Alps with snow fir and met a Korean mafia.
It gives everything in these imaginary facts, everything is real, even later in the memories.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dreaming is a different state, so describe your experience.
On the contrary, the memories of mental journeys are, many years later, much clearer, even in irrelevant details.
It’s even brighter and more intense than real experiences.
The intensity of this experience dilutes the horizon of the rest of our daily experiences, adds psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Finally, oneirism, psychosis, hallucinations, and drug use show how fragile the inner reproduction of external reality is, even when we are awake.
Any modification of the state of consciousness, psychologist Kasten summarizes, “can lead to a deformation of what we call reality.”
An experience that, on the other hand, can be completely enriching.
